## Species Overview {#overview}

The **goldfish** (*Carassius auratus*) is the oldest ornamental fish in human history. Selective breeding of wild *Carassius* carp began in Tang Dynasty China approximately 1,200 years ago, and over the subsequent millennia, Chinese, Japanese, and later Western breeders developed over 200 distinct varieties from the same ancestral wild carp — creating the fantails, orandas, ryukins, ranchus, bubble eyes, and dozens of other forms that represent one of the most dramatic examples of artificial selection in animal domestication history.

Goldfish are not beginner fish in small tanks. This is one of the most damaging myths in the aquarium hobby. The goldfish's reputation as a disposable fairground prize, appropriate for bowls and tiny tanks, has caused the deaths of hundreds of millions of fish. In appropriate conditions, goldfish are long-lived, intelligent, and remarkably rewarding animals — some living 20–30 years and reaching 25–40cm in length.

### Scientific Classification

| Rank | Classification |
|------|----------------|
| Kingdom | Animalia |
| Phylum | Chordata |
| Class | Actinopterygii |
| Order | Cypriniformes |
| Family | Cyprinidae |
| Genus | *Carassius* |
| Species | *C. auratus* |

*Carassius auratus* is classified within the carp family Cyprinidae, and is more closely related to koi (*Cyprinus carpio*) than commonly appreciated — the two species can hybridize, though resulting offspring are usually infertile. The wild ancestor of the goldfish is the Prussian carp (*Carassius gibelio*) of East Asia, a drab olive-green fish that shows spontaneous gold/orange mutations in wild populations.

