## Aquarium Care Requirements {#aquarium-care}

### The Space Requirement Explained

Adult fancy goldfish require significantly more space than standard community fish of similar size. A single fancy goldfish (oranda, ryukin, etc.) requires a minimum **75–90 litres (20–25 US gallons)**, with an additional 35–40 litres per additional goldfish. This is not an arbitrary rule — it reflects the waste production, oxygen consumption, and swimming requirements of the animal.

Single-tailed goldfish varieties (commons, comets, shubunkins) grow even larger (30–40cm+) and are not appropriate for indoor tanks at all — they belong in outdoor ponds.

### Water Parameters

| Parameter | Optimal Range | Acceptable Range |
|-----------|--------------|-----------------|
| Temperature | 16–22°C (61–72°F) | 10–26°C |
| pH | 7.0–8.0 | 6.5–8.5 |
| General Hardness (GH) | 8–16 dGH | 5–20 dGH |
| Carbonate Hardness (KH) | 6–12 dKH | 4–15 dKH |
| Ammonia | 0 ppm | — |
| Nitrite | 0 ppm | — |
| Nitrate | <20 ppm | <40 ppm |

Note the temperature range: 16–22°C is optimal. Goldfish kept consistently at tropical temperatures (25–28°C) have shortened lifespans, increased susceptibility to disease, and diminished immune function. They should **not** be kept in tropical community tanks.

