## Tank Setup Guide {#tank-setup}

### The Goldfish Environment

**Filtration:** Goldfish need powerful filtration — a filter rated for at least 2–3x the tank volume per hour, and many experienced keepers use 4–6x. A canister filter for mechanical and biological filtration is ideal. Sponge pre-filters on the intake prevent fin and tail damage.

**Substrate:** Sand or smooth pea gravel. Goldfish are benthic foragers — they sift substrate constantly. Fine sand is ideal; very small gravel creates impaction risk as goldfish ingest it while foraging. Large smooth rocks decorating the tank are appropriate.

**Plants:** A challenge. Goldfish eat virtually all soft-leaved plants. Options: tough plants they won't eat (*Anubias*, Java Fern, hornwort — which they do eat but grows fast enough to keep up), plastic plants (ensure no sharp edges), or a goldfish pond without plants.

**Aeration:** Goldfish consume significant dissolved oxygen. In warm weather especially, an air stone adds meaningful oxygen to prevent the surface-gulping behavior that indicates low DO.

**Water Changes:** More frequent than tropical tanks. 25–30% weekly minimum; many experienced keepers do 50% weekly for fancy goldfish. The goal is keeping nitrates below 20 ppm despite the high waste load.

> Use the [Water Change Calculator](/tools/water-change) to calculate exactly how many changes are needed to reach target nitrate levels in a goldfish tank.

