## Varieties and Morphs {#morphs}

The diversity of goldfish varieties is unmatched in any domesticated fish species. A brief overview of major groups:

### Single-Tail Varieties (Pond Fish)
**Common goldfish:** The ancestral form; olive-bronze to bright orange-red. Grows 25–35cm. Pond fish only.
**Comet goldfish:** Long, forked tail; active, hardy, fast. 25–35cm. Pond fish.
**Shubunkin:** Calico coloration (blue, white, red, orange, black) on a transparent-scaled body. Pond fish.

### Double-Tail Fancy Varieties (Aquarium Fish)
**Fantail:** The foundation fancy variety; double tail held high, egg-shaped body. 15–20cm.
**Ryukin:** Pronounced shoulder hump behind the head; double tail; vivid coloration. 15–22cm.
**Oranda:** Hood-like wen (fleshy growth) on the head; double tail. Wens can grow to cover the eyes — monitor and trim if necessary.
**Lionhead:** No dorsal fin; large wen covering the entire head. Requires careful water quality management as wen tissue is prone to infection.
**Ranchu:** The Japanese equivalent of the lionhead; arched back, no dorsal fin, highly developed wen. The premier show variety in Japan.
**Pearlscale:** Rounded body with dome-shaped scales that give a golf-ball texture appearance. Distinctive but fragile — the protruding scales are easily damaged.
**Telescope Eye / Moor:** Protruding eyes on stalks; black variety = "black moor." Eyes are highly vulnerable to infection and damage; requires special care and smooth décor.
**Bubble Eye:** Enormous fluid-filled sacs below the eyes that wobble as the fish swims. The most extreme and fragile variety; cannot be kept with other fish.
**Celestial Eye:** Upward-pointing eyes; cannot see below them. Must be kept species-only.

